headline.main: AMERICAN SLAVERY.; Professor Ansted's Letters--No. II.
LATEST INTELLIGENCE; By Telegraph to the New-York Daily Times FROM WASHINGTON. Foreign Appointments--Panama Consul-The Turkish Mission--An Issue--Enterprising Ohio Boy--Removals. &c.

docs.lead_paragraph: The Foreign appointments have hitched again. None were officially announced to-day, although that of RICHARD KIBDER MEADE to Chili, is given out as certain. A long session of the Cabinet was held to-day, relative to the Foreign Missions exclusively. The rumor of the selection of Gen. DIX for the Mission to France, gains strength.

byline.original: Special Dispatch to the New-York Daily Times

docs.lead_paragraph: We have been waiting some time for action on behalf of the sewing women. A strike among seamstresses can hardly be spared from the multitude of similar movements marking the day. Their prices are sadly low. The labor is exhausting, careful, health-destroying.

docs.lead_paragraph: FOR LIBRRIA.--The ship Banshee sailed from Baltimore for Liberia on Monday, conveying 117 emigrants. This vessel was chartered by the Chesapeake and Liberia Trading Company for the voyage out, and will be discharged at Cape Palmas.

headline.main: NEW-YORK CITY.; Opinion of Judge Nelson in the matter of Thomas Kaine, claimed as a Fugitive from Justice under the Trenty between the United States and Great Britalu. Aug. 9, 1842.

docs.lead_paragraph: UNITED STATES CIRCUIT CUURT--AT CHAMBERS.--Judge NELSON said: This case should have been disposed of at an earlier day; but having heard it in the midst of a circuit, the constant pressure of business upon the Jury calendar has compelled me to postpone the consideration of it.

headline.main: The Romance of History--Captain Kidd and Robin Hood.

docs.lead_paragraph: In the House of Commons, on the 11th inst., the third reading of the Canadian Clergy Reserves Bill was carried by a majority of 80 in favor of the Ministry. In the House of Lords, on that day, nothing of importance was transacted.

headline.main: The Late Disturbance at Greytown.; To the Editor of the New-York Daily Times:

docs.lead_paragraph: In the New-York Herald of the 1st inst., I notice a communication signed "H," professing to give a true and accurate account of the late disturbance at this port. The object of that letter, it is easy to perceive, was to place the Commander of the Cyane before the public in a false position.

docs.lead_paragraph: An ordinance has been reported to the City Council of Boston, to establish the office of a superintendent of the Internal Health Department, who shall have the care and superintendence of the city carts and stables, and shall make all necessary arrangements for cleaning the streets, disposing of manure, and removing house dirt and house offal.
